  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div id="faq" class="mt-10 mb-6 not-prose">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">What causes a disc stack centrifuge bowl to clog?</summary>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm mt-3">The most common causes are excess sludge in the process fluid (often from a settled feed tank), a sludge discharge timer set too long, failure of the sludge discharge mechanism, or solids lighter than the process liquid that migrate into the disc stack rather than the sludge space.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">How do I clean a clogged disc stack centrifuge?</summary>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm mt-3">Two methods: (1) Complete bowl disassembly — stop the centrifuge, disassemble the bowl, and clean each disc individually (soaking in diesel overnight for severe clogging). (2) For minor clogging, run multiple timed discharge cycles with clean fluid to flush sludge out incrementally. If performance does not recover, full disassembly is required.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">How can I prevent disc stack clogging?</summary>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm mt-3">Agitate the feed tank constantly to keep sludge in suspension, monitor process fluid sludge content regularly, install a centrate outlet pressure sensor with feed shutoff interlock, and verify that sludge discharge cycles are completing normally each shift.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">What are the symptoms of a clogged disc stack centrifuge?</summary>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm mt-3">Unexplained reduction in centrate flow rate, higher-than-normal vibration levels due to unbalanced sludge accumulation, and degraded separation quality with phase cross-contamination — light phase in the heavy phase outlet or vice versa.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">Can sludge discharge cycles clear a clogged disc stack without disassembly?</summary>
        <p class="text-text-light text-sm mt-3">For minor clogging, running multiple timed discharge cycles with clean fluid can sometimes flush sludge from the disc stack incrementally. However, if separation performance does not recover within a few cycles, full bowl disassembly and manual cleaning of each disc is required. Attempting to operate a severely clogged centrifuge can cause vibration, safety hazards, and accelerated wear.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>

